      </subsection>

      <subsection name="Java">

      <blockquote>  
        <table>
         <tr>
          <td>Overall</td>
   <td>
     <em><img src='../images/overall.png' alt='overall icon'/></em> 
   </td>
   <td>
          <a href='http://java.com/en/download/help/'>Sun's Java Virtual Machine</a>, JVM 6 (or 5). 
          In most modern systems it is pre-installed in some form.
          The JVM is also called the Java runtime environment (JRE) or just Java. <!-- http://java.com/en/download/help/ --> 
          A Java development kit (JDK) contains a JVM.
   </td>
	 </tr>
         <tr>
          <td>
           Tested
          </td>
   <td>
     <em><img src='../images/tested.png' alt='Tested icon'/></em> 
   </td>
          <td>Hippo continuously tests the ECM with 
              <a href='http://java.com/en/download/index.jsp'>Java JVM 6 as 
              supplied by Sun Microsystems</a>. Occasionally it is tested 
              with <span class=''>Linux Ubuntu package sun-java6-jre</span>.
          </td>
   <!--
        <ul>
          <li><p>Sun JVM</p></li>
          <li><p>IBM JVM</p></li>
          <li><p>BEA JRockit</p></li>
        </ul>
    -->
	 </tr>
      <tr>
       <td>
         Acquire
       </td>
   <td>
     <em><img src='../images/acquire.png' alt='Acquire icon'/></em> 
   </td>
   <td>      
          Sun's Java JVM 6 (or 5) 
          can be acquired from 
          <a href='http://java.com/en/download/index.jsp'>Sun Microsystems</a>, 
          from websites of Linux distributions 
          (e.g. 
           <a href='http://packages.ubuntu.com/'>Ubuntu</a>: 
           <a href='http://packages.ubuntu.com/hardy/sun-java6-jre'>JRE 6</a>
           <a href='http://www.debian.org/distrib/packages'>Debian</a>:
           <a href='http://packages.debian.org/lenny/sun-java6-jre'>JRE 6</a>,
           ) 
          and in other ways. Only packages 
          that ask you to agree to Sun's licence terms contain Java from
          <a href='http://www.sun.com/'>Sun Microsystems</a> and will run the Hippo ECM.
      <p> 
          In pure <a href='http://www.gnu.org/copyleft/gpl.html'>GPL</a> 
          distributions like <a href='http://www.debian.org'>Debian Linux</a>,
          such packages are forbidden in section `main' and can therefor
          never be pre-installed. They can however be found in section `non-free' and
          installed additionally (e.g. <a href='http://packages.debian.org/lenny/sun-java6-jdk'>JDK 6</a>). 
          Most Linux distributions have less strict rules.         
      </p>
   </td>
      </tr>
	</table>
      </blockquote>

      </subsection>


      <subsection name="Java Servlet Container">

      <blockquote>  
        <table>
         <tr>
          <td>Overall</td>
   <td>
     <em><img src='../images/overall.png' alt='overall icon'/></em> 
   </td>
   <td>Hippo ECM works in any Java Servlet container, conforming to version
       <span class='confirm'>2.4</span> of the 
       <a href='http://java.sun.com/products/servlet/reference/api/index.html'>Sun Servlet container 
       specification</a>. <!-- alt: http://java.sun.com/products/servlet/download.html#specs -->
       Java application servers include the functionality of Java Servlet containers, so
       can also be used.
   </td>
   </tr>
 
         <tr>
          <td>
           Tested
          </td>
   <td>
     <em><img src='../images/tested.png' alt='Tested icon'/></em> 
   </td>
          <td>
              <span class='expires'>Hippo continuously tests the ECM with 
               <a href='http://jetty.mortbay.com/jetty/'>Jetty</a> 6.1
               and also often with 
               <a href='http://tomcat.apache.org/'>Tomcat</a> 6. 
               Occasionally it is tested 
               with                
               <a href='https://glassfish.dev.java.net/public/users.html'>Sun GlassFish</a> V2.
               All these tested servlet and application
               containers are origional, no packages supplied by websites of Linux distributions.
              </span>
       <span class='expires'>
        The <a href='http://packages.ubuntu.com/hardy/glassfishv2'>Linux Ubuntu package of Glassfish V2</a>
        was reported in Sept 2008 to run
        Hippo ECM, but a bug has to be avoided (see Warnings).
       </span>
          </td>
	 </tr>

      <tr>
       <td>
         Acquire
       </td>
   <td>
     <em><img src='../images/acquire.png' alt='Acquire icon'/></em> 
   </td>
   <td>    
       Java servlet containers and application servers can be aquired from 
       Apache, Sun, as Linux Packages and from many more sources.   

       E.g.: 
       <a href='http://jetty.mortbay.com/jetty/'>Jetty</a> 6.1
       can be obtained from Hippo: it is included in the
       quickstart-bin package: 
       <a href='../delve_into/quickstart.html'>Quickstart</a>, or
        from codehaus
       <a href='http://docs.codehaus.org/display/JETTY/Downloading+Jetty'>Jetty 6.1 download</a>.          
       <a href="http://tomcat.apache.org/download-60.cgi">Tomcat 6.0 from Apache</a>.
       <a href='http://packages.ubuntu.com/hardy/glassfishv2'>Linux Ubuntu package of Glassfish V2</a>
       (use apt-get, aptitude or synaptic for easy installation).       
   </td>
      </tr>

      <tr>
       <td>
         Warnings
       </td>
   <td>
     <em><img src='../images/warnings.png' alt='Warn icon'/></em> 
   </td>
   <td>    
      <span class='expires'>
        The application server JBoss was reported in Sept 2008 not to run Hippo ECM.
      </span>
      <span class='expires'>
        The Debian package of the servlet container Tomcat 5.5 was reported in Aug 2008 not to run
        Hippo ECM.
      </span>
      <span class='expires'>
        The <a href='http://packages.ubuntu.com/hardy/glassfishv2'>Ubuntu package Glassfish V2</a> 
        works, but only if
        dpkg-reconfigure is never used on the package, as the package 
        contains a 
        <a href='https://bugs.launchpad.net/ubuntu/+source/glassfishv2/+bug/257362'>severe bug with respect to this command</a>. 
      </span>
   </td>
      </tr>

	</table>
      </blockquote>

